properties.name: Advice
properties.location: the King River at Docker Road
properties.webBody:
This is a Final Minor Flood Warning for the King River at Docker Road. 

FLOODING IS NO LONGER EXPECTED ALONG THE KING RIVER AT DOCKER RD BRIDGE

In the last 24 hours to 9:00am Saturday rainfall totals of 10 to 20 millimetres have been recorded across the King River catchment. Rainfall has eased since early Saturday morning, with no further significant rainfall forecast. 

No further flooding is expected in the King River.

The King River at Docker Road Bridge is currently at 2.41 metres and steady, and is likely to peak below the minor flood level of 3.70 metres is Saturday afternoon.
The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and floodwater in low lying areas may still be present in the area. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning for this flood. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Barham to Wakool Junction.

  • The Murray River at Wakool Junction is currently at 8.64 metres and steady. 
  • The Murray River at Wakool Junction is likely to exceed the minor flood level (8.80 metres) around Sunday. The river level may reach 9.10 metres around mid August, with minor flooding. 
  • Further rises are possible.
This message is for communities in Victoria. Flood impacts vary along the Murray River between NSW and Victoria. For information and warnings relevant to NSW, please check www.ses.nsw.gov.au. Always follow the instructions provided by your state's emergency services.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Monitor local conditions, stay out of closed parks including tracks and roads and travel using recommended routes.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Check VicTraffic (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and always follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Some parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds may be closed due to flooding. To find out more visit the Parks Victoria (parks.vic.gov.au) website.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 07/08/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:

  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT KIEWA (MAIN STREAM) AND BANDIANA FROM SATURDAY AFTERNOON

River level rises are being observed and minor flooding is possible from Saturday afternoon along the Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) and Bandiana.

Rainfall totals up to 35 millimetres have been recorded in the Kiewa River catchment in the 24 hours to 9 am Saturday. No further significant rainfall is expected.

Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge:
Minor flooding is possible along the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge. The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is currently at 2.44 metres and rising, below the minor flood level 3.30 metres. 

The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) may exceed the minor flood level 3.30 metres Saturday afternoon. 

The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.31 metres and steady, below the minor flood level 2.80 metres. The Kiewa River at Bandiana is likely to exceed the minor flood level 2.80 metres Saturday evening.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 06/08/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.location: Murray River downstream of Torrumbarry to Barham
properties.webBody:
This Minor to Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Torrumbarry to Barham.

Minor to moderate flooding is occurring along the Murray River downstream of Torrumbarry to Barham. These increased flows are due to rain events that occurred in the Upper Murray Catchment during June and early July, with this water now slowly moving downstream.

  • The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir peaked at 7.48 metres around 07:00 am Friday 28 July and is currently at 7.33 metres and falling slowly, with minor flooding. The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir is expected to fall below the minor flood level (7.30 metres) around Friday afternoon.    
  •  The Murray River at Barham is steady near a peak of 5.96 metres, with moderate flooding. The Murray River at Barham is likely to remain above the moderate flood level (5.80 metres) into mid-August.
This message is for communities in Victoria. Flood impacts vary along the Murray River between NSW and Victoria. For information and warnings relevant to NSW, please check www.ses.nsw.gov.au. Always follow the instructions provided by your state's emergency services.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
More information:
  • The Murray River at Echuca is currently at 91.53 metres Australian Height Datum (AHD), and has dropped 40cm since Saturday 29 July.
  • For August to October, the Bureau of Meteorology (BOM) predicts below median rainfall is likely to very likely for most of Australia and above median maximum temperatures are very likely for almost all of Australia. This forecast is influenced by several factors, including likely El Nino development, the potential development of a positive Indian Ocean Dipole, and record warm oceans globally.
What you should do:
  • Monitor local conditions, stay out of closed parks including tracks and roads and travel using recommended routes.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • This flood will likely be contained within forested areas.
  • Check VicTraffic (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and always follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Some parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds may be closed due to flooding. To find out more visit the Parks Victoria (parks.vic.gov.au) website.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 07/08/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
